{"cursor":"50146","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn theoretical physics, the 'EinsteinâCartan theory', also known as the\n'EinsteinâCartanâSciamaâKibble theory' or the 'CartanâSciamaâKibble theory' is a\nclassical theory of gravitation similar to general relativity but relaxing the\nassumption that the metric be torsion-free. Introducing torsion allows greater\nfreedom to couple classical spin angular momentum to the metric. The theory was\nfirst proposed by Ãlie Cartan in 1922 Ãlie Cartan. \"Sur une gÃ©nÃ©ralisation\nde la notion de courbure de Riemann et les espaces Ã  torsion.\" C. R. Acad. Sci.\n(Paris), 174:593â595, 1922. and expounded in the following few\nyears. Ãlie Cartan. \"Sur les variÃ©tÃ©s Ã  connexion affine et la thÃ©orie de la\nrelativitÃ© gÃ©nÃ©ralisÃ©e.\" Part I: Ann. Ãc. Norm. 40: 325â412 and ibid. 41: 1â25;\nPart II: ibid. 42: 17â88 Dennis Sciama and Tom Kibble independently\nrevisited the theory in the 1950s, and an important review was published in\n1976. Friedrich W. Hehl, Paul von der Heyde, G. David Kerlick, and James M.\nNester. \"General relativity with spin and torsion: Foundations and prospects.\"\nRev. Mod. Phys. 48, 393â416 (1976)\nhttp://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/RevModPhys.48.393 Albert Einstein became\naffiliated with the theory in 1928 during his unsuccessful attempt to match\ntorsion to the electromagnetic field tensor as part of a unified field theory.\nThis line of thought led him to the related but different theory of\nteleparallelism. Hubert F. M. Goenner. [http://relativity.livingreviews.org/Articles/lrr-2004-\n2/ \"On the History of Unified Field Theories.\"] Living Rev. Relativity, 7,\n(2004), 2.\n\nEinsteinâCartan theory has been historically overshadowed by its torsion-free\ncounterpart and other alternatives like BransâDicke theory because torsion\nseemed to add little predictive benefit at the expense of the tractability of\nits equations. In particular, many effects of nonzero torsion are hypothesized\nto be non-propagating so that its direct observation is expected to be\ndifficult. Sean Carroll and George Field. [http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-\nqc/9403058v2 \"Consequences of Propagating Torsion in Connection-Dynamic Theories\nof Gravity.\"] Phys. Rev. D50 (1994) 3867-3873. Since EinsteinâCartan\ntheory is purely classical, it also does not fully address the issue of quantum\ngravity. Interest in EinsteinâCartan theory has been renewed in recent years,\nhowever, as theorists try to incorporate torsion into novel quantum theories or\nas they explore its cosmological implications. The theory is still considered viable and remains an active\ntopic in the physics community. Friedrich Hehl. [http://ptonline.aip.org/journals/doc/PHTOAD-\nft/vol_60/iss_3/16_2.shtml \"Note on the torsion tensor.\"] Letter to Physics\nToday. March 2007, page 16.\n","linknr":451,"url":"Einstein-Cartan_theory","recorded":1363121942,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Einstein%E2%80%93Cartan_theory&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Einstein%E2%80%93Cartan_theory&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Einstein%E2%80%93Cartan_theory","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Einstein-Cartan_theory&redirect=no","#mw-head","#p-sea